CuddleBit

I feel like the robot is angry and wants to punch something like that, but its not like hes lost his mind, hes still under control.

How can simple breathing movements express complicated and nuanced emotions? What about on a non-anthropomorphic robot?  We explored this possibility through iterative robot motion design and user studies.

This work was accepted by CHI 2018.

Challenges

Many technologies for social purposes require expressing emotions in order to communicate effectively with their users. Social robots, for example, should be emotionally responsive, no matter if it's a treatment bot or a virtual pet. There were findings on factors contributing to the intensity of a emotion feels. Identifying the positivity of a emotion expression is however a tricky task. While a smiling face is commonly used as the signal of positive emotions, it can be negative at times - people smile when they're nervous or angry. We need a better understanding on human perception of robots who do not have facial expression or voice to talk - what emotion do their body movements talk to us? 

 

We approach this challenge from two perspectives: (i) we computationally analyzed characteristics of the movement; (ii) we explored how much contextual information influences emotion expression. 

Process

This project went through three major phases described in the chart on the right. We began with exploring potential factors influencing emotion perception indicated in the literature, from where we noticed an interesting trend: emotions described as complicated are perceived to be more negative.

We focused on this finding and iterated several ways to analyze and control the complexity of robots' behaviors. In a user study, we evaluated how these complexity based motion manipulation influences perception of our robots' emotions. 

This process demonstrates our attempt to non-verbally express emotions from motions. We hoped to understand how much emotional information we can computationally retrieve without explicit contexts.

Behaviour Design and Iterations

Our first attempt was inspired by the field of Biology and Physiology. Three statistics were considered as potential measures of complexity for a signal: Variance (var), Spectral Density (extracted from fft) and Multi-scale Entropy (MSE). 

Using Generic Algorithm, we generated sample behaviours with different complexity levels, and ran a piloting study on it. However, pilot results showed small emotional differentiability among behaviors. One explanation the team had was that signals generated by Generic Algorithm don't result in meaningful behaviors. 

 

We therefore decided to evaluate existing behaviors (partly from a database previously designed by other teams and partly new behaviors designed by myself with varying narratives). We wrote a Python script to analyze the above three statistical measures of each behavior.

 

To fast prototype these behaviors, we made use of two design tools that I helped with programming (both using Arduino and ReactJs): 

Voodle

a voice input design interface that you can use to design robot motions with emotional sounds - "Wow!", "Oh nooo", or "Meowmeow". 

MacaronBit

A keyframe editor tool that allows further refining of robots' motions.

Result 

Through ANOVA analysis on ratings of the emotion positivity of three groups of behaviors (Variance, Spectral Density, and MSE), we see promising trends on the effects of behavioural complexity on positivity of the behaviour, especially MSE. 

At the same time, we found that people often project very different narratives and assumptions to animal like objects. Those different assumptions - i.e. some participants regarded the robot as a dog, lead to very distinctive perceptions of robots' emotion. 

My vision of future research includes to apply machine learning to extract other motion characteristics that contribute to emotion positivity. Ways to control users' assumptions on robots are very valuable to technologies on this topic too. 

 

Demonstration

To gain further understanding on how people perceive emotions based on motion patterns and contexts, and to demonstrate our approach of computationally differentiating behavioral signals' emotions, we submitted a proposal to CHI 2018 demonstration. 

In this demonstration, we set up a fast-prototype kit for demonstration attendees to build their own robots based on a specific kind of emotion they choose:

Their prototyped robot puppets were then filmed and shared on social media - search "cuddlebits" on Twitter to see their interesting products!
